Using the results of these tests, I model the binary variable “obtaining contact,” using a random effects (two-level) logit model with waves as the first level and households as the second. Note that variables that change over time affect the first level, while variables that change across households affect the second. Before I fit the multilevel model, I test contact efficiency improvement using a logistic regression model on pairwise combinations of the following variables:


household characteristics (number of persons, child present, retired or unemployed person);



time of day; and



day of the week (Monday–Friday or Saturday).

Specifically, I enter the following variables into a backward selection regression (removal level: .01), to test for entry into the two-level model:


(time of day) × household size;



(time of day) × child present;



(time of day) × retired person present;



(day of the week) × household size;



(day of the week) × child present;



(day of the week) × retired person present;



(time of day) × (day of the week);



all main effects;



the control variables wave (1–5: linear), original sample (vs. refreshment from 2004, binary), refusal conversion phase (vs. not, binary), and “Swiss German–speaking” (vs. French/Italian, binary). The idea to include the latter is to capture different at-home patterns due to cultural differences or different lifestyles (e.g., Koch et al. 2009); and



if the call time window coincides with the time of day at which the household was first contacted in the previous wave (set to 0 if no previous wave available).

The backward logistic regression removes all interaction variables with the exception of:


(weekday evening) × (retired person in household);



(Saturday) × (retired person in household);



(weekday early afternoon) × (child in household);



(weekday late afternoon) × (child in household); and



(weekday evening) × (child in household).

The main effects are kept, with the exception of wave and sample.
